  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions against money laundering, including:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- International standards for combating money laundering\n- 40 recommendations widely adopted by countries globally\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Provides framework for international cooperation\n- Signed by over 190 countries\n\n3. Basel Committee Guidelines\n- Banking regulations to prevent financial crimes\n- Establishes due diligence standards\n\n4. The Egmont Group\n- International network of financial intelligence units\n- Facilitates information sharing between countries\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Comprehensive regulations for EU member states\n- Regularly updated to address emerging risks\n\nMost countries have national laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Conduct ongoing monitoring\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
